Day 5 — Build Integration and Build Info
What is Build Info?
Build Info is Artifactory's traceability mechanism — a JSON document that records everything about a build:

Which artifacts were published (uploaded) by this build
Which artifacts were resolved (downloaded/used as dependencies) by this build
Build number, timestamp, build agent, environment variables
VCS information (Git commit, branch)
This creates a complete audit trail: "This JAR file was built from commit abc123 on branch main by Jenkins build #42, using these exact dependency versions."

Why Build Info Matters
Traceability — trace any artifact back to its source code
Reproducibility — know exactly what went into a build
Security — identify which builds used a vulnerable dependency
Compliance — prove what was deployed and when

Build Integration with CI Tools
JFrog integrates with all major CI/CD tools:

Jenkins — JFrog Jenkins plugin
GitHub Actions — jfrog/setup-jfrog-cli action
GitLab CI — JFrog CLI in pipeline
Azure DevOps — JFrog extension
JFrog Pipelines — native integration
Build Lifecycle in Artifactory

1. CI resolves dependencies → downloaded from Artifactory Virtual repo
2. CI builds the artifact
3. CI uploads artifact → to Artifactory Local repo
4. CI publishes Build Info → links artifact to its dependencies and VCS
5. Promotion → artifact moves from dev repo to staging/prod repo

Promotion
Promotion is the act of moving or copying an artifact from one repository to another as it passes through stages (dev → staging → production).

libs-snapshot-local → (promote after testing) → libs-release-local
docker-dev-local    → (promote after approval) → docker-prod-local

Promotion preserves the artifact — you're not rebuilding. The same binary that passed testing is what goes to production.
